Understanding the basics of cancer subtyping tasks, the results will be reused for the current paper

Thuc Le

17 July 2017

1. Introduction: Identifying Breast Cancer Subtypes

Breast cancer is not a single disease and identifying breast cancer subtypes helps us understand the heteroginity of the disease and assists with the prognosis and design of personalised treatments. The IHC method groups patients into 3 subtypes using pathological markers: ER+, HER+, and triple negative.

Molecular subtyping provides a more comprehensive explanation of what and how the subtype develops. There are several approaches of subtyping breast cancer using gene expression data. However, the commonly accepted approaches are:

  1. 4 intrinsic subtypes defined by Perou et al: Luminal A, Luminal B, HER2-enriched, and Basal. The method is based on hierrachical clustering and using gene expression data for the analysis. In practice, PAM50 provides a tool for predicting the subtype of single sample that outputs subtypes similar to ones defined by Perou. Subtypes predicted by PAM50 include: LumA, LumB, Basal, HER2-enriched, and Normal like.Gene expression profiles will be the input for PAM50.

  2. 10 intrinsic subtypes developed by METABRIC group and use icluster as the clustering methods for integrating multiple data types.The relationship between the 10 subtypes and the 4 subtypes is shown in the reviews by Caldas and Xifiang Dai.

2. Datasets

We have pre-processed the breast cancer datasets, including:

  1. TCGA expression data with 753 matched samples of miRNA-mRNA-clinical data,
  2. 500 samples of miRNA-mRNA-lncRNA-clinical data,
  3. 1980 matched samples of miRNA-mRNA-clinical METABRIC data.
  4. UK dataset with matched miRNA-mRNA-clinical (to be processed)

The aims are to understanding existing approaches of cancer subtyping and prognosis for breast cancer and try to develop new methods using miRNA and/or lncRNA data on top of mRNA data. Lets play with METABRIC data firstly:

3. Experiments

3.1 Identify cancer subtypes based on METABRIC dataset

Now we will try to subtyping METABRIC dataset using PAM50 and IntClust from the genefu package:

3.1.1 Data processing

METABRIC_mRNA= read.csv(file="METABRIC_mRNA_2017.csv", header=TRUE, sep=",")
MBR_miR=read.csv(file="METABRIC_miRNA.csv", header=TRUE, sep=",")
MBR_clin=read.csv(file="METABRIC_clinical.csv", header=TRUE, sep=",")

MBR_mRNA_Anno = METABRIC_mRNA[,1:2]
colnames(MBR_mRNA_Anno) = c("Gene.Symbol", "EntrezGene.ID")
mRSamples = colnames(METABRIC_mRNA[3:ncol(METABRIC_mRNA)]) #The first 2 columns are gene names
mRSamples = gsub("\\.", "-", mRSamples) #replace "." with "-" to be consistent with clinical sample names
MBR_mRData = METABRIC_mRNA[, 3:ncol(METABRIC_mRNA)]
MBR_mRData = t(MBR_mRData)
colnames(MBR_mRData)= MBR_mRNA_Anno$Gene.Symbol
rownames(MBR_mRData)= mRSamples

MBR_miRNA_Anno = MBR_miR[,1:2]
colnames(MBR_miRNA_Anno) = c("Probe", "miRNA")
miRSamples = colnames(MBR_miR[3:ncol(MBR_miR)]) 
miRSamples = gsub("\\.", "-", miRSamples)
MBR_miRData = MBR_miR[, 3:ncol(MBR_miR)]
MBR_miRData = t(MBR_miRData)
colnames(MBR_miRData)= MBR_miRNA_Anno$miRNA
rownames(MBR_miRData)= miRSamples

clinSamples=MBR_clin$PATIENT_ID


##get intersection and match sampes
intersect_samples=Reduce(intersect,  list(v1 = mRSamples, 
                                          v2 = miRSamples, 
                                          v3 = clinSamples))
intersect_samples=sort(intersect_samples)
index1=match(intersect_samples,mRSamples)
index2=match(intersect_samples,miRSamples)
index3=match(intersect_samples,clinSamples)
MBR_mRData=MBR_mRData[index1,]
MBR_miRData=MBR_miRData[index2,]
MBR_clin=MBR_clin[index3,]
all(rownames(MBR_mRData)==rownames(MBR_miRData))
all(rownames(MBR_mRData)==MBR_clin$PATIENT_ID)

save(MBR_mRData,MBR_miRData,MBR_clin,MBR_mRNA_Anno,MBR_miRNA_Anno, file="METABRIC1.rda")

                               annot=MBR_mRNA_Anno,do.mapping=FALSE)

3.1.3 Consensus clustering

#Average the expression of each miRNA over the probes of the same miRNA symbol, or keep the probe that is more variant.
# Get matched samples of miRNA, mRNA, clinical

data=t(MBR_mRData)
##use the median to impute the missing values
data1=data.imputation(data, fun = "median")
METABRIC_CC=ExecuteCC(clusterNum=5,d=data1,maxK=5,clusterAlg="hc",distance="pearson",title="METABRIC_CC")
## end fraction
## clustered
## clustered
## clustered
## clustered
table(METABRIC_CC$group)
## 
##    1    2    3    4    5 
## 1277    3    1    1    1
##Comments: the RNAseq data (before nomalization) always return very extreme result. This is maily caulsed by the outlier
##and the Mean-Shift amony samples.

## data nomalization
data2=data.normalization(data1)
METABRIC_CC=ExecuteCC(clusterNum=5,d=data2,maxK=5,clusterAlg="hc",distance="pearson",title="METABRIC_CC")
## end fraction
## clustered
## clustered
## clustered
## clustered
table(METABRIC_CC$group)
## 
##   1   2   3   4   5 
## 300 552  55 371   5
## feature selction and nomalization
data3=FSbyMAD(data1, cut.type = "topk", 12000)

data4=data.normalization(data3)
METABRIC_CC=ExecuteCC(clusterNum=5,d=data4,maxK=5,clusterAlg="hc",distance="pearson",title="METABRIC_CC")
## end fraction
## clustered
## clustered
## clustered
## clustered
table(METABRIC_CC$group)

##   1   2   3   4   5
